with 110 direct flights a day
due to be coming

11:55.481 --> 11:59.352 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
here from later in the year. So,
I have been
talking to Cubans who, for
example, for the

11:59.385 --> 12:05.058 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
last year have been able to rent
out their
homes through Airbnb, that
American service

12:05.091 --> 12:07.694 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on the Internet where you let
out your homes
to people.

12:07.727 --> 12:11.431 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, Cubans for years have been
letting out
their rooms. They call it casas
particulares,

12:11.464 --> 12:18.338 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but now it's on the Web. Here in
Havana, there
2,500 homes that are being
rented out on Airbnb.

12:18.371 --> 12:23.576 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And people are so pleased to
have the extra
money, because the average Cuban
wage is about

12:23.610 --> 12:25.411 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
25 U.S. dollars a month.

12:25.445 --> 12:31.651 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Through Airbnb, the average
amount you get
from a stay is $250. So, there
is a huge change

12:31.684 --> 12:35.855 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
for people who regularly
complain that they
just do not have enough money to
live on.

12:35.888 --> 12:39.626 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Yet, when the two
presidents talk
about -- admit that they have --
still have

12:39.659 --> 12:45.732 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
profound differences between the
two nations,
does that trickle down at all to
ordinary

12:45.765 --> 12:46.633 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Cubans?

12:46.666 --> 12:48.568 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LAURA TREVELYAN: Well, most
certainly.

12:48.601 --> 12:55.408 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As someone who's lived in
America 12 years,
coming here to Havana, Cuba,
what strikes

12:55.441 --> 13:00.279 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you is that this is a one-party
state, that
broadcasting is
state-controlled.

13:00.313 --> 13:05.485 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, for example, this morning,
on morning
television, there was respectful
TV coverage

13:05.518 --> 13:10.923 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the Obama visit, pictures of
the Obama
girls under an umbrella,
pictures of Michelle

13:10.957 --> 13:13.493 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
coming down from Air Force One.

13:13.526 --> 13:17.664 align:left position:25%,start line:73.33% size:75%
But the tone is
state-controlled. And it was
made clear in the coverage that
Guantanamo

13:17.697 --> 13:21.634 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Bay is something that will be
raised. And
then, of course, related to that
is the fact

13:21.668 --> 13:26.606 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that there isn't freedom of
information here,
because the Internet service is
terrible.

13:26.639 --> 13:32.278 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One of the changes that Raul
Castro has introduced,
is there is more public Wi-Fi in
public parks,

13:32.311 --> 13:37.417 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but Cubans have to pay for it.
And the young
Cubans that I have been speaking
to, their

13:37.450 --> 13:41.788 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
biggest wish is that the
Internet service
could be better, so that they
could be online,

13:41.821 --> 13:45.191 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
so they can use Facebook, they
can use Twitter,
they can use e-mail.

13:45.224 --> 13:49.829 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They just feel that their lives
are so restricted.
As one young Cuban said to me,
"Knowledge

13:49.862 --> 13:54.300 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is power, and without the
Internet, we can't
have the information we need to
make choices

13:54.333 --> 13:55.835 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
about our lives."

13:55.868 --> 13:58.471 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: It's something,
watching change
happen right before our eyes.

13:58.504 --> 14:03.443 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Laura Trevelyan reporting for
the BBC and
for us from Havana tonight,
thank you.

14:03.476 --> 14:09.115 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And we turn to
analysis of
today's historic meeting in
Havana and of

14:09.148 --> 14:11.150 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the president's trip to Cuba.

14:11.184 --> 14:17.090 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For that, I'm joined by Maria de
Los Angeles
Torres, director of the
Inter-University Program

14:17.123 --> 14:22.829 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for Latino Research and a
professor at the
University of Illinois, Chicago.
And Roger

14:22.862 --> 14:28.501 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Noriega of the American
Enterprise Institute.
He's a former assistant
secretary of state

14:28.534 --> 14:32.805 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for Western Hemisphere affairs
in the George
W. Bush administration.

14:32.839 --> 14:35.208 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And we welcome you both.

14:35.241 --> 14:36.576 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Roger Noriega, to you first.

14:36.609 --> 14:39.412 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What's your impression so far of
how this
trip is going?

14:39.445 --> 14:42.281 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROGER NORIEGA, Former U.S.
Assistant Secretary
of State: Well, it was a little
clumsy today,

14:42.315 --> 14:45.551 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I think, the very awkward press
conference.

14:45.585 --> 14:53.159 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But I can understand the
excitement of the
Cuban people that was described
by your previous

14:53.192 --> 14:57.630 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
guest. You know, there is
something sort of
exotic about Cuba. People
haven't been able

14:57.663 --> 15:03.336 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to travel there in a long time.
It's a tropical
island. It has a shortages of
fish and tropical

15:03.369 --> 15:06.839 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
fruit. Something clearly is
wrong there.

15:06.873 --> 15:12.011 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, on the other hand, the
people aren't
that different than people
anywhere. And they

15:12.044 --> 15:19.252 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- you know, why would anybody
choose to be
in a dictatorship? Why wouldn't
they choose

15:19.285 --> 15:26.459 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
democracy? Because the
government has a totalitarian
hold on every aspect of their
lives.

15:26.492 --> 15:30.830 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that worries me, because the
government,
in the final analysis, will have
the say of

15:30.863 --> 15:37.837 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
whether the economic opening
achieves any
sort of meaningful change or
whether the people

15:37.870 --> 15:39.272 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
are going to be left
disappointed.

15:39.305 --> 15:41.307 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Maria Torres,
what's your sense
of the trip so far?

15:41.340 --> 15:44.210 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARIA DE LOS ANGELES TORRES,
University of
Illinois at Chicago: Well, for
not only for

15:44.243 --> 15:48.381 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Cubans on the island, but I
think for Cubans
like myself that came to the
United States

15:48.414 --> 15:52.585 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
as young children, this has been
very moving.

15:52.618 --> 15:58.991 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it is historic, even though
that is a
very overused word when we speak
about Cuba.

15:59.025 --> 16:04.931 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I would like to just remind all
of us that
this is not the first time that
we have had

16:04.964 --> 16:11.504 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a rapprochement with Cuba. In
1978, Jimmy
Carter also opened the door. In
fact, there

16:11.537 --> 16:17.844 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
was another historic moment in
which a Cuban
airline landed in Atlanta and
took over 100

16:17.877 --> 16:20.313 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Cuban Americans to dialogue with
the Cuban
government.

16:20.346 --> 16:25.084 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Actually, that was my first trip
back to Cuba.
We were very excited at the
time. We thought

16:25.117 --> 16:31.891 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that there could be change.
There was 3,600
political prisoners that were
released, and,

16:31.924 --> 16:35.561 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in fact, small businesses were
opened up at
the time.

16:35.595 --> 16:43.035 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But what happened was that it
got out of control
and the Cuban government opened
up the floodgates,

16:43.069 --> 16:48.808 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and at the same time clamped
down. And after
that came Reagan. So, I am
hopeful, to the

16:48.841 --> 16:55.948 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
extent that I think this is a
little bit more,
if you will, assertive
rapprochement on the

16:55.982 --> 17:01.220 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
part of President Obama, but we
still need
to remember it is a military
government.

17:01.254 --> 17:04.991 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Roger Noriega, do
you think
this time will be different? Do
you see something

17:05.024 --> 17:10.463 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
materially different this time?
Obviously,
the president's there, but what
do you believe

17:10.496 --> 17:12.231 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
could come from this?

17:12.265 --> 17:15.301 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROGER NORIEGA: Well, certainly,
that's very
dramatic. The president's made a
big bet on

17:15.334 --> 17:17.770 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
this in terms of his legacy in
history.

17:17.803 --> 17:23.042 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Unfortunately, if he loses that
bet, it's
going to be 11 million Cubans
that pay the

17:23.075 --> 17:29.949 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
price, because by licensing
deals, as he has,
tractor factory and...

17:29.982 --> 17:31.684 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Business deals.

17:31.717 --> 17:35.054 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROGER NORIEGA: .... hotels being
-- several
hotels being managed, these are
deals that

17:35.087 --> 17:40.760 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
he's licensed with entities that
are owned
and operated by the Cuban
military.

17:40.793 --> 17:44.563 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, in a certain way, you know,
we sort of
counted on the actuarial table
to deal with

17:44.597 --> 17:52.338 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the Castro brothers, but by the
president
sort of not only giving the
political normalization

17:52.371 --> 17:58.411 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and legitimization, but also
this economic
engagement, it may actually
create a certain

17:58.444 --> 18:06.252 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
momentum for transition in the
post-Castro
period to just more dictators.

18:06.285 --> 18:09.021 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think that would be
extraordinarily
tragic if that were to happen.

18:09.055 --> 18:12.858 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Maria Torres,
could that be
an outcome of this, that the
communist regime

18:12.892 --> 18:17.330 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is strengthened by this, rather
than moving
toward -- in any way toward
democracy?

18:17.363 --> 18:21.901 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARIA DE LOS ANGELES TORRES:
Well, I think
there's always -- that's a risk,
but I also

18:21.934 --> 18:24.870 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
think that there's a couple of
factors that
are different this time around.

18:24.904 --> 18:30.609 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that is, one, I think there
is support
on this side of the Florida
Strait. Many of

18:30.643 --> 18:36.616 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the businesses today in Cuba are
being fueled
by family members who are in
Miami. There

18:36.649 --> 18:41.287 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is -- that's a very porous
border. I think
that the Cuban government
realizes they do

18:41.320 --> 18:47.093 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
not have Soviet Union or a
Venezuela or Brazil
or Chinese government that will
bail them

18:47.126 --> 18:50.563 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
out this time around. And so,
therefore, they
are forced to make changes.

18:50.596 --> 18:55.401 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I don't think these are changes
that they
want to make. And they are, in
fact, very

18:55.434 --> 19:00.606 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
modest changes, given the depth
of the crisis
in Cuba. But, nonetheless, I
think for those

19:00.639 --> 19:06.212 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who would like to be part of
whatever configuration
of a government there is after
the Castro

19:06.245 --> 19:10.082 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
brothers, there is a sense that
they have
got to make some changes.

19:10.116 --> 19:16.422 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And one thing Cuba cannot do is
open up the
immigration floodgates, and so,
therefore,

19:16.455 --> 19:19.725 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it is internally that the
changes have to
be made.

19:19.759 --> 19:23.295 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, let's pick
up on that
and pick up on the political
prisoner exchange

19:23.329 --> 19:25.131 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
at today's news conference.

19:25.164 --> 19:31.303 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Roger Noriega, we saw President
Castro fire
back. He said, what political
prisoners? And

19:31.337 --> 19:34.440 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
he said, give me a list and we
will release
them tonight.

19:34.473 --> 19:38.044 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What do you see going on there?
Because now
there are human rights
organizations saying,

19:38.077 --> 19:39.845 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
we're going to put out the
names.

19:39.879 --> 19:44.650 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROGER NORIEGA: Well, quite
frankly, I can
see why he would lose track of
the political

19:44.683 --> 19:48.621 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
prisoners, because they take
them every day,
and the arrests were very
dramatic because

19:48.654 --> 19:55.995 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they were on the eve of the
president's visit,
the arrests yesterday of ladies
going to church,

19:56.028 --> 20:01.133 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Santeria Parish, as they do
every Sunday.
They are beaten up and roughed
up every Sunday

20:01.167 --> 20:02.601 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
as well, so...

20:02.635 --> 20:04.437 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And this is just
on the eve
of President Obama arriving?

20:04.470 --> 20:10.142 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROGER NORIEGA: Absolutely. And
that just sort
of affirms that the regime is
not going to

20:10.176 --> 20:17.349 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
let up. And they have every
intention of holding,
you know, sort of restraining
any kind of

20:17.383 --> 20:21.187 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
economical or political opening
that would
threaten its survival.

20:21.220 --> 20:27.026 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Maria Torres, why
isn't that
a pretty discouraging
development here, that

20:27.059 --> 20:31.497 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
there really is very little sign
so far of
their move toward democracy and
certainly

20:31.530 --> 20:34.567 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
not toward doing anything about
these prisoners,
political prisoners?

20:34.600 --> 20:36.535 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARIA DE LOS ANGELES TORRES: I
absolutely
agree.

20:36.569 --> 20:40.339 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think one thing we have to
remember, change
doesn't necessarily mean it's
going to be

20:40.372 --> 20:47.980 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
positive. And I think, with the
crumbling,
if you will, of totalitarian
regimes oftentimes

20:48.013 --> 20:50.649 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
comes a moment of extreme
repression.

20:50.683 --> 20:58.958 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think that is why the fact
that Raul
Castro was asked on his own turf
about political

20:58.991 --> 21:03.796 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
prisoners and about human rights
is something
that we normally don't see. And
I think that

21:03.829 --> 21:11.637 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that, regardless of how little
Internet there
is in Cuba and how little press
there is,

21:11.670 --> 21:13.472 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
people in Cuba will know this by
tonight.

21:13.506 --> 21:18.611 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so I think that that is --
in a sense,
that is creating another sense
of environment,

21:18.644 --> 21:24.783 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and in fact, I would say a sense
of empowerment.
The repression -- as one of the
leaders of

21:24.817 --> 21:29.088 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the human rights groups in Cuba
said today,
there is a lot of repression
because there

21:29.121 --> 21:31.357 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is a lot of democracy movement
on the ground.

21:31.390 --> 21:36.695 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Roger Noriega, so
could there
be empowerment just by the very
fact that

21:36.729 --> 21:42.401 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they had the president's visit
and this news
conference, that people will ask
questions?

21:42.434 --> 21:47.673 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROGER NORIEGA: I think this is a
very tough
totalitarian Stalinist regime,
as it's been

21:47.706 --> 21:53.078 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
described to me by Eastern
Europeans who've
lived there, but it's also a
brittle regime,

21:53.112 --> 21:55.147 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in my way of thinking.

21:55.181 --> 22:04.223 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think that this is one
area. Can the
regime control expectations? If
that gets

22:04.256 --> 22:11.163 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
out of hand, it will be a
serious problem.
But my concern is that, did the
president

22:11.197 --> 22:17.269 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
strengthen Castro's hand by
accepting engagement
with Cuba on his terms?

22:17.303 --> 22:21.674 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The regime has made this a
binary choice.
You either engage the regime or
you engage

22:21.707 --> 22:28.280 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
the people. And since
Eisenhower, presidents
have chosen not to engage the
people. And

22:28.314 --> 22:32.685 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm afraid that this sends the
wrong message,
and the president also making a
commitment,

22:32.718 --> 22:35.821 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a statement that he's not about
changing the
regime.

22:35.854 --> 22:40.993 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, why wouldn't he be? This
is a totalitarian
regime. Why wouldn't anybody be
for changing

22:41.026 --> 22:42.795 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
that regime?

22:42.828 --> 22:44.697 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: We're going to
have to leave
it there, but we thank you both
very much,

22:44.730 --> 22:48.667 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Roger Noriega, Maria de Los
Angeles Torres.
Thank you.

22:48.701 --> 23:00.646 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARIA DE LOS ANGELES TORRES:
Thank you.

